Singapore Stocks: Amtek, Neptune Orient, Overseas Union, PEC

-- B y   J o n a t h a n   B u r g o s
-- 
2011-08-25T04:34:11Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-08-25/singapore-stocks-amtek-neptune-orient-overseas-union-pec.html
Singapore ’s Straits Times Index
gained 1.4 percent to 2,758.77 as of 12:30 p.m. local time, set
for its biggest advance since Aug. 12. Six stocks rose for each
that fell in the index of 30 companies.  The following shares were among the most active in the
market. Stock symbols are in parentheses after the company name.  Export-related companies: Shares of shipping companies,
port operators and electronics manufacturers rose after a report
showed orders for U.S. durable goods climbed 4 percent in July
as demand for aircraft and cars surged. That beat the median
forecast of 2 percent in a Bloomberg survey of economists.
Orders excluding the volatile transportation category
unexpectedly advanced 0.7 percent.  Neptune Orient Lines Ltd. (NOL SP), a container carrier
that gets about 55 percent of revenue from the “Americas,”
rose 1.5 percent to S$1.04. Hutchison Port Holdings Trust (HPHT
SP), the owner of port assets in  Hong Kong  and  China , climbed
2.5 percent to 62 U.S. cents.  Amtek Engineering Ltd. (AMTK)  ,
a supplier of precision components to companies including Sony
Corp., gained 2.3 percent to 66 Singapore cents.  Overseas Union Enterprise Ltd. (OUE)  , a Singapore-based
hotel operator, surged 3.9 percent to S$2.40. The company said
it will seek a mandate from shareholders to buy back its own
shares.  PEC Ltd. (PEC)  , a provider of engineering services to
the oil, gas and pharmaceutical industries, slumped 6.7 percent
to 83 Singapore cents, poised for its biggest drop since
November 2009. The company said full-year net income dropped 28
percent from a year earlier to S$32.1 million ($27 million).  To contact the reporter on this story:
Jonathan Burgos in Singapore at 
